http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/Phase-one-delay-hampers-Muziris-project%E2%80%99s-marketing/article14003974.ece

The inordinate delay in launching phase one of Muziris Heritage Project has thrown into disarray Kerala Tourism’s plans to market the locale, tourism officials said.We are unable to begin full-fledged marketing of the locale, launch the official website, logo and promotional videos, release a coffee-table book and introduce online payments.Moreover, second phase works can gain pace if the first phase comprising seven museums and four sites – two forts and two markets - are formally opened to visitors, they said.The sprawling Paliam museum and Paravur synagogue are two main heritage attractions that have been conserved.Inviting PresidentTill December, tourism officials were pinning hopes on Prime Minister Narendra Modi inaugurating phase one during his Kerala visit. Subsequently, they are expected to extend invitation to President Pranab Mukherjee. “Every effort is being made to launch the project in February and we hope to get confirmation from the President.”Panel worksEven as detractors claim that many works are not over, tourism mandarins say that only panel works on the Islamic history museum is pending.The first phase costs Rs.108.5 crore, for which the Centre pooled in Rs.42 crore and State Rs.52 crore. The PWD spent Rs.10 crore for readying roads and allied infrastructure, while Irrigation Department was given Rs.4.50 crore for building boat jetties.A total of 26 museums are expected to be conserved as part of Muziris project. This includes a maritime museum spread over 50 acres. The State government is expected to allot Rs.25 crore each year for the initiative.A delegation from Member of Parliament Local Area Development, headed by Thambi Durai, MP, had visited the museums a week ago.